		<description><![CDATA[You will be able to see Woman Shaman, since it is a dvd that will ship to Europe, and quite affordable. Some clips will be viewable online as well. I agree that the technology rests on some very distressing foundations, such as Apple&#039;s slavery-in-all-but-name factories in China. However, since the scientistic mechanistic worldview is a reaction to extremely destructive Christian dogma, i see them as connected, by contrast with Indigeous cosmovisions. Think of &quot;subdue the earth,&quot; and the continuities there in today&#039;s industrialized corporate feudalism. I see &quot;that beautiful image of God&quot; as part of the problem, because it was so thoroughly masculinized, hegemonic, and made separate from our consciousness and from the material world. Those schisms have to be overcome, in my view, and replaced with recognition of the interconnectedness of all things, &quot;All our relations&quot; as the Lakota say. A Christianity based in the Beatitudes would have been far less problematic, but as some have said, it turned into Paulinianity, with heavy infusions of Roman authoritarianism, which i personally can&#039;t relate to.]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>You will be able to see Woman Shaman, since it is a dvd that will ship to Europe, and quite affordable. Some clips will be viewable online as well. I agree that the technology rests on some very distressing foundations, such as Apple&#8217;s slavery-in-all-but-name factories in China. However, since the scientistic mechanistic worldview is a reaction to extremely destructive Christian dogma, i see them as connected, by contrast with Indigeous cosmovisions. Think of &#8220;subdue the earth,&#8221; and the continuities there in today&#8217;s industrialized corporate feudalism. I see &#8220;that beautiful image of God&#8221; as part of the problem, because it was so thoroughly masculinized, hegemonic, and made separate from our consciousness and from the material world. Those schisms have to be overcome, in my view, and replaced with recognition of the interconnectedness of all things, &#8220;All our relations&#8221; as the Lakota say. A Christianity based in the Beatitudes would have been far less problematic, but as some have said, it turned into Paulinianity, with heavy infusions of Roman authoritarianism, which i personally can&#8217;t relate to.</p>
