		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.sourcememory.net/veleda/?p=179#comment-501</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Not at all. You didn&#039;t read carefully enough to put aside your assumptions. How did you miss this: &quot;Counter to the modern market-driven shaman-fad, the shaman is chosen by the spirits, not self-selected. Initiation cannot be purchased, and boasting is a sure sign of pretense. Instead of self-indulgence and ego-boosting, the medicine woman puts in intensive effort, sacrifice, hardship, and suffering.&quot; 

However, all people have the potential to access these states of consciousness, and in many cultures there is a continuum, with participation by the community -- chanting, clapping, dancing -- in which the shamanic ritual creates a shared transformative experience. In some regions there may be only a few shamans, while in others, such as the San Ju/hoan &quot;Bushmen,&quot; a significant portion of the population may be considered in this light.]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Not at all. You didn&#8217;t read carefully enough to put aside your assumptions. How did you miss this: &#8220;Counter to the modern market-driven shaman-fad, the shaman is chosen by the spirits, not self-selected. Initiation cannot be purchased, and boasting is a sure sign of pretense. Instead of self-indulgence and ego-boosting, the medicine woman puts in intensive effort, sacrifice, hardship, and suffering.&#8221; </p>
<p>However, all people have the potential to access these states of consciousness, and in many cultures there is a continuum, with participation by the community &#8212; chanting, clapping, dancing &#8212; in which the shamanic ritual creates a shared transformative experience. In some regions there may be only a few shamans, while in others, such as the San Ju/hoan &#8220;Bushmen,&#8221; a significant portion of the population may be considered in this light.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
